## Chapter 8 A Better Way For Anisotropic Solids

This chapter is a loose retelling of SS4 and SS5 from Kim et al. (2019). If you want to cut to the chase, the Matlab code that spits out the analytic eigenvalues of an anisotropic energy is given in SS8.2.5.

### 8.1 What's Anisotropy?

So far, we have looked at _isotropic_ solids. If you squish them down, they bulge out the exactly the same amount in all directions. If you stretch them out, they resist the same amount, no matter which direction you're pulling in. Most real-world solids don't do this exactly; they can be stiffer in some directions and softer in others.

Let's compare a length of rubber band and a length of hemp rope sagging under gravity (Fig. 8.1).

The rubber band sags a whole bunch. While the rope sags too, it doesn't dip as far down, because it is composed of bundles of stiff fibers that all run in a single, preferred direction. In the extreme, if we ran a steel reinforcement rod down the length of the rope, it wouldn't sag at all.

Figure 8.1: **Left pair:** A length of rubber band sags a lot under gravity. **Right pair:** A length of hemp rope sags less, because it contains stiff fibers that all run in a preferred direction.

#### 8.1.3 A Better Way For Anisotropic Solids

The material is _anisotropic_. It's stiffer in some directions than it is in others.

The same thing can happen in a volumetric solid. When we squash down an isotropic material (Fig. 8.2), it bulges out equally in all directions.

If the solid contains fibers that all run in a specific direction, then it will be reluctant to pooch out in that direction.1 One everyday material that does this is _biological muscle_. All the muscles in your body contain fibers, and when you flex a muscle, your brain is telling those aligned fibers to contract, i.e. _become shorter_ (Fig. 8.3).

Footnote 1: Avi Goyal suggested another (totally separate) example: trying to squash a block of Post-It Notes. Pound on top with your fist, and basically nothing happens. But pinch it along the sides with your fingers, and it pooches out easily.

When these fibers become shorter, they pull on the bones on either ends of the muscle, and that's why your body moves. End of anatomy lesson.

Figure 8.2: **Left pair:** An isotropic material bulges out equally in all directions **Right pair:** Fiber reinforcement has been inserted, so it bulges less in that direction. The lines along the front remain vertical.

### 8.2 The (Wrong) Cauchy-Green Invariants, Again

#### The \(Iv_{\mathbf{C}}\) and \(V_{\mathbf{C}}\) Invariants

How do we tell our energies that there's a preferred anisotropy direction that we want to be stiffer? Even if we have some anisotropy direction \(\mathbf{a}\in\Re^{3}\) in mind, there's nowhere to plug it into our existing invariants.

In biomechanics (see e.g. the survey of Chagnon et al. (2015)), this is solved by introducing a new set of invariants that explicitly take into account some vector \(\mathbf{a}\). These new invariants gets stacked onto the end of our existing sequence of Cauchy-Green invariants:2

Footnote 2: If you’re a real invariant nerd, it may bother you that these invariants don’t actually arise from the characteristic polynomial of \(\mathbf{F}\). Where’s their generating equation? I don’t know. They’re definitely translation and rotation invariant though, so they at least fit the definition of “invariant” in that sense.

\[IV_{\mathbf{C}}=\mathbf{a}^{T}\mathbf{Ca} V_{\mathbf{C}}=\mathbf{a}^{T}\mathbf{C}^{T}\mathbf{Ca}, \tag{8.1}\]

where, as before, \(\mathbf{C}=\mathbf{F}^{T}\mathbf{F}\). The anisotropy direction only needs to be defined _at the rest shape_ (Fig. 8.4).

To see why, we can unpack \(IV_{\mathbf{C}}\) into:

\[IV_{\mathbf{C}}=\mathbf{a}^{T}\mathbf{F}^{T}\mathbf{F}\mathbf{a}=\left( \mathbf{F}\mathbf{a}\right)^{T}\mathbf{F}\mathbf{a}=\left(\mathbf{D}_{s} \mathbf{D}_{m}^{-1}\mathbf{a}\right)^{T}\mathbf{D}_{s}\mathbf{D}_{m}^{-1} \mathbf{a}. \tag{8.2}\]

On the right, we can see that the invariant is just two applications of \(\mathbf{D}_{s}\mathbf{D}_{m}^{-1}\mathbf{a}\). The first multiply, \(\mathbf{D}_{m}^{-1}\mathbf{a}\), rotates the fiber direction out of the original rest shape. Then it gets rotated into the current deformation by the second multiply, \(\mathbf{D}_{s}\). Thus, the invariant will automatically transform the original \(\mathbf{a}\) into the appropriate orientation for the current deformation.

#### Gradients and Hessians, Again

Let's look at how to take the gradient and Hessian of an anisotropic energy.

Figure 8.4: The anisotropy direction \(\mathbf{a}\) only needs to be defined _at the rest shape_. It gets automatically carried along as the object deforms.

##### 8.2.2.1 Anisotropic St. Venant Kirchhoff

There's a bunch of different anisotropic energies appearing in the literature that we can pick from, but for some reason people seem reluctant to name them. This one appears in anonymous form in both Liu et al. (2017) and Holzapfel (2005):

\[\Psi_{\text{AStVK}}=\frac{\mu}{2}\left(IV_{\mathbf{C}}-1\right)^{2}. \tag{8.3}\]

Since it follows the StVK approach of squaring a \(\mathbf{C}\)-like term, let's call it _Anisotropic StVK_. The gradient and Hessian are,

\[\frac{\partial\Psi_{\text{AStVK}}}{\partial\mathbf{F}} =\mu\left(IV_{\mathbf{C}}-1\right)\frac{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}} {\partial\mathbf{F}} \tag{8.4}\] \[\mathrm{vec}\left(\frac{\partial^{2}\Psi_{\text{AStVK}}}{ \partial\mathbf{F}^{2}}\right) =\mu\left(\left(IV_{\mathbf{C}}-1\right)\mathbf{H}_{IV}+\mathbf{ g}_{IV}\mathbf{g}_{IV}^{T}\right), \tag{8.5}\]

where

\[\frac{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}}{\partial\mathbf{F}} =2\mathbf{Faa}^{T} \tag{8.6}\] \[\mathbf{g}_{\text{IV}} =\mathrm{vec}\left(\frac{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}}{\partial \mathbf{F}}\right)=\mathrm{vec}\left(2\mathbf{Faa}^{T}\right)\] (8.7) \[\mathbf{H}_{IV} =\mathrm{vec}\left(\frac{\partial^{2}IV_{\mathbf{C}}}{\partial \mathbf{F}^{2}}\right)=2\mathbf{aa}^{T}\otimes\mathbf{I}. \tag{8.8}\]

Rather than slugging through these derivatives every time, just like in the isotropic case (Eqns. 5.8 and 5.50), there is a generic, oh-thank-my-lucky-stars-I-only-need-scalar-derivatives way of deriving the Hessian:

\[\mathrm{vec}\left(\frac{\partial^{2}\Psi}{\partial\mathbf{F}^{2}}\right)=\frac {\partial\Psi}{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}}\mathbf{H}_{IV}+\frac{\partial^{2}\Psi }{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}^{2}}\mathbf{g}_{IV}\mathbf{g}_{IV}^{T}. \tag{8.9}\]

Once you have the relatively easy \(\frac{\partial\Psi}{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}}\) and \(\frac{\partial^{2}\Psi}{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}^{2}}\) terms worked out3, you're all done.

Footnote 3: Again, don’t be ashamed to use Mathematica or Matlab. Really.

##### 8.2.2.2 Anisotropic Square Root

Let's try the generic approach on another (usually unnamed) energy that appears in biomechanics (Alastrue et al. (2008)):

\[\Psi_{\text{ASqrt}}=\frac{\mu}{2}\left(\sqrt{IV_{\mathbf{C}}}-1\right)^{2}. \tag{8.10}\]It's almost exactly the same as the Anisotropic StVK energy, except for the square root. For that reason, let's call it the _Anisotropic Square Root_ model. The gradient is:

\[\frac{\partial\Psi_{\text{ASqrt}}}{\partial\mathbf{F}}=\mu\left(1-\frac{1}{\sqrt{ IV_{\mathbf{C}}}}\right)\mathbf{Faa}^{T}. \tag{8.11}\]

We can get the Hessian by taking the scalar derivatives,

\[\frac{\partial\Psi_{\text{ASqrt}}}{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}}=\frac{\mu}{2} \left(1-\frac{1}{\sqrt{IV_{\mathbf{C}}}}\right) \frac{\partial^{2}\Psi_{\text{ASqrt}}}{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}^{2}}= \frac{\mu}{4IV_{\mathbf{C}}^{\frac{3}{2}}},\]

and plugging them in to get our final Hessian4:

Footnote 4: This expression looks slightly different from the one I gave in Kim et al. (2019) because I pushed some factors of 2 around in a different way. However, I assure you that if you work through all the terms, they are indeed equivalent.

\[\operatorname{vec}\left(\frac{\partial^{2}\Psi_{\text{ASqrt}}}{\partial \mathbf{F}^{2}}\right)=\frac{\mu}{2}\left(1-\frac{1}{\sqrt{IV_{\mathbf{C}}}} \right)\mathbf{H}_{IV}+\frac{\mu}{4IV_{\mathbf{C}}^{\frac{3}{2}}}\mathbf{g}_ {IV}\mathbf{g}_{IV}^{T}. \tag{8.12}\]

All done. Except that the Hessian might be indefinite.

#### 8.2.3 The Eigensystem of \(IV_{\mathbf{C}}\)

With Eqn. 8.9 in hand, we can apply the same approach as SS7.3. If we can get an analytic expression for the eigendecomposition of \(\mathbf{H}_{IV}\), then we can get the analytic eigenstructure of _any_ energy based on \(IV_{\mathbf{C}}\).

Fortunately, Matlab hack-and-slashing quickly reveals that the eigensystem of \(\mathbf{H}_{IV}\) has a rank-six null-space, so there are only three non-trivial eigenpairs:

\[\lambda_{0,1,2} =2 \tag{8.13}\] \[\mathbf{Q}_{0} =\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf{a}^{T}\\ 0&0&0\\ 0&0&0\end{bmatrix} \mathbf{Q}_{1} =\begin{bmatrix}0&0&0\\ \mathbf{a}^{T}&\\ 0&0&0\end{bmatrix} \mathbf{Q}_{2} =\begin{bmatrix}0&0&0\\ 0&0&0\\ \mathbf{a}^{T}\end{bmatrix}. \tag{8.14}\]

First off, it _is_ an arbitrary subspace, so the forms given for \(\mathbf{Q}_{0,1,2}\) are not unique. They're convenient to write in this form though. Second, the most general form of the eigenvalues is \(\lambda_{0,1,2}=2\|\mathbf{a}\|_{2}^{2}\), but usually a is specified as a unit vector. The purpose of a is to convey that you want things stiffer in _this_ direction, but the amount of stiffness you want would be communicated by some sort of \(\mu\) constant. Baking it into the magnitude of a would just cause confusion.

#### 8.2.4 The Eigensystems of Arbitrary \(Iv_{\mathbf{C}}\) Energies

With the eigensystem of \(\mathbf{H}_{IV}\) in hand, we can now build the eigensystems of arbitrary \(IV_{\mathbf{C}}\)-based energies. Looking again at the generic form of these Hessians,

\[\operatorname{vec}\left(\frac{\partial^{2}\Psi}{\partial\mathbf{F}^{2}}\right)= \frac{\partial\Psi}{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}}\mathbf{H}_{IV}+\frac{\partial^{ 2}\Psi}{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}^{2}}\mathbf{g}_{IV}\mathbf{g}_{IV}^{T},\]

we already know the eigensystem of the first term on the right, \(\frac{\partial\Psi}{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}}\mathbf{H}_{IV}\). The eigenvectors are still those from Eqn. 8.14, and the eigenvalues all get scaled by \(\frac{\partial\Psi}{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}}\).

Adding the \(\frac{\partial^{2}\Psi}{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}^{2}}\mathbf{g}_{IV}\mathbf{g }_{IV}^{T}\) term complicates things, because (again) there's no general theorem that helps you get the eigensystem of a sum of matrices, even if you already know the eigensystems of the summands. But, while we're not adding to a diagonal matrix like we did in SS7.2 and SS7.3, we're doing something similar. We're adding a rank-one update, \(\mathbf{g}_{IV}\mathbf{g}_{IV}^{T}\), to a matrix with an arbitrary subspace, \(\mathbf{H}_{IV}\).

In our case, what happens is that _one_ of the directions in the arbitrary subspace gets pinned to \(\mathbf{g}_{IV}\), i.e. the direction of the rank-one update. The other two directions are still arbitrary, but they then get pinned to the subspace that is orthogonal to \(\mathbf{g}_{IV}\).

More concretely, the first eigenpair is:

\[\lambda_{0}=2\left(\frac{\partial\Psi}{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}}+2IV_{\mathbf{C }}\frac{\partial^{2}\Psi}{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}^{2}}\right)\qquad\qquad \qquad\mathbf{Q}_{0}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{IV_{\mathbf{C}}}}\mathbf{Faa}^{T}. \tag{8.15}\]

Keeping in mind that \(\mathbf{g}_{IV}=2\operatorname{vec}\left(\mathbf{Faa}^{T}\right)\), the eigenmatrix \(\mathbf{Q}_{0}\) has indeed been pinned to a normalized version of \(\mathbf{g}_{IV}\).

The other two eigenvalues are:

\[\lambda_{1,2}=2\frac{\partial\Psi}{\partial IV_{\mathbf{C}}}. \tag{8.16}\]

The arbitrary subspace takes a little effort to construct, and in practice you never actually compute these explicitly. However, to show that it _can_ be done, we first define the twist matrices,

\[\mathbf{T}_{x}=\begin{bmatrix}0&0&0\\ 0&0&1\\ 0&-1&0\end{bmatrix}\qquad\qquad\mathbf{T}_{y}=\begin{bmatrix}0&0&-1\\ 0&0&0\\ 1&0&0\end{bmatrix}\qquad\qquad\mathbf{T}_{z}=\begin{bmatrix}0&1&0\\ -1&0&0\\ 0&0&0\end{bmatrix}.\]

Since the last two eigenvectors are arbitrary, you have to pick one of these matrices to start with. Just for the sake of argument, let's pick \(\mathbf{T}_{x}\). Then the second eigenmatrix becomes:

\[\mathbf{Q}_{1}=\mathbf{U}\mathbf{T}_{x}\Sigma\mathbf{V}^{T}\mathbf{A}. \tag{8.17}\]This effectively pins third eigenmatrix, which can be written in terms of \(\mathbf{T}_{y}\) and \(\mathbf{T}_{z}\),

\[\mathbf{Q}_{2}=(\sigma_{y}\hat{\mathbf{a}}_{y})\mathbf{U}\mathbf{T}_{z}\Sigma \mathbf{V}^{T}\mathbf{A}-(\sigma_{z}\hat{\mathbf{a}}_{z})\mathbf{U}\mathbf{T}_{y }\Sigma\mathbf{V}^{T}\mathbf{A}, \tag{8.18}\]

where \(\hat{\mathbf{a}}_{y,z}\) are the corresponding entries from \(\hat{\mathbf{a}}=\mathbf{V}^{T}\mathbf{a}\).

#### Matlab/Octave Implementation

Code that implements these expressions is given in Fig. 8.5, and examples running them on \(\Psi_{\text{AS}}\) and \(\Psi_{\text{Sqrt}}\) are in Fig. 8.6. Using these scripts, we obtain the following analytic eigenvalues for Anisotropic StVK,

\[\lambda_{0} =2\mu(I_{5}-1)+4\mu I_{5} \tag{8.19}\] \[\lambda_{1,2} =2\mu(I_{5}-1). \tag{8.20}\]

and for Anisotropic Square Root:

\[\lambda_{0} =\mu \tag{8.21}\] \[\lambda_{1,2} =\mu\left(1-\frac{1}{\sqrt{I_{5}}}\right). \tag{8.22}\]

### Better Invariants, Again

#### An Inversion-Aware Invariant

The energies we've looked all suffer from a version of the problem we saw in SS6.1.2. They can't tell if an element has been poked inside-out, i.e. inverted / reversed / prolapsed.

